00:09:15.160 --> 00:09:16.879
Best wishes, John Green

00:09:16.879 --> 00:09:20.160
But back to the Junzi: So how do you know
how to behave? Well, first you have to look

00:09:20.160 --> 00:09:25.319
to historical antecedents, particularly the
sage emperors. The study of history, as well

00:09:25.319 --> 00:09:30.339
as poetry and paintings in order to understand
and appreciate beauty, is indispensable for

00:09:30.339 --> 00:09:34.839
a Junzi. The other important aspects of Junzi-ness
are contained in the Confucian ideas of ren

00:09:34.839 --> 00:09:39.259
and li. Ren and Li are both incredibly complex
concepts that are difficult to translate,

00:09:39.259 --> 00:09:41.009
but we’re going to do our best.

00:09:41.009 --> 00:09:44.699
Ren is usually translated as “propriety”.
It means understanding and practicing proper

00:09:44.699 --> 00:09:48.589
behavior in every possible situation, which
of course depends on who you’re interacting

00:09:48.589 --> 00:09:53.050
with, hence the importance of the five relationships.
Li is usually translated as “ritual” and

00:09:53.050 --> 00:09:56.509
refers to rituals associated with Chinese
religion, most of which involve the veneration

00:09:56.509 --> 00:09:57.410
of ancestors.

00:09:57.410 --> 00:10:00.939
Which brings us back, in a very roundabout
way, to the fundamental problem of how early

00:10:00.939 --> 00:10:05.019
Chinese historians wrote their history. Traditional
Chinese historians were all trained in the

00:10:05.019 --> 00:10:10.999
Confucian classics, which emphasized the idea
that good emperors behaved like good Confucians.

00:10:10.999 --> 00:10:14.839
Would-be historians had to know these classics
by heart and they’d imbibed their lessons,

00:10:14.839 --> 00:10:19.600
chief among which was the idea that in order
to maintain the Mandate of Heaven, you had

00:10:19.600 --> 00:10:25.569
to behave properly and not engage in orgies
or eat your enemies or eat your enemies while

00:10:25.569 --> 00:10:27.079
engaging in orgies.

00:10:27.079 --> 00:10:31.989
In this history the political fortunes of
a dynasty ultimately rest on one man and his

00:10:31.989 --> 00:10:36.569
actions - whether he behaves properly. The
Mandate of Heaven is remarkably flexible as

00:10:36.569 --> 00:10:40.579
an explanation of historical causation. It
explains why, as dynasties fell, there were

00:10:40.579 --> 00:10:46.069
often terrible storms and floods and peasant
uprisings... If the emperor had been behaving

00:10:46.069 --> 00:10:47.670
properly, none of that stuff would have happened.

00:10:47.670 --> 00:10:51.839
Now, a more modern historian might point out
that the negative effects of terrible storms

00:10:51.839 --> 00:10:57.529
and floods, which includes peasant uprisings,
sometimes lead to changes in leadership. But

00:10:57.529 --> 00:11:00.929
that would take the moral aspect out of history
and it would also diminish the importance

00:11:00.929 --> 00:11:02.600
of Confucian scholars.

00:11:02.600 --> 00:11:06.649
Because the scholars can tell you that one
of the best ways to learn how to be a good

00:11:06.649 --> 00:11:12.110
emperor, and thereby maintain the Mandate
of Heaven, is to read the Confucian Classics,

00:11:12.110 --> 00:11:14.160
which were written by scholars.

00:11:14.160 --> 00:11:18.489
In short, the complicated circularity of Chinese
history is mirrored by the complicated circularity

00:11:18.489 --> 00:11:22.589
of the relationship between those who write
it and those who make it. Which is something

00:11:22.589 --> 00:11:26.160
to think about no matter what history you’re
learning, even if it’s from Crash Course.

